Creating a Server in Node.js

Node.js provides the http module to create a web server.

1. Import http Module
const http = require('http');
2. Create Server
const server = http.createServer((req, res) => {
    res.end("Hello World");
});
Explanation:
req → request object (client request)
res → response object (server response)
3. Start Server (listen)
server.listen(3000, () => {
    console.log("Server running at http://localhost:3000");
});
Meaning:
Server runs on port 3000

Access via browser:

http://localhost:3000
4. Basic Routing Example
const http = require('http');

const server = http.createServer((req, res) => {

    if (req.url === '/' && req.method === 'GET') {
        res.end("Home Page");
    }
    else if (req.url === '/about' && req.method === 'GET') {
        res.end("About Page");
    }
    else {
        res.statusCode = 404;
        res.end("Not Found");
    }

});

server.listen(3000, () => {
    console.log("Server running at http://localhost:3000");
});
5. Set Response Headers
res.writeHead(200, { 'Content-Type': 'text/plain' });
res.end("Hello World");
Common Content Types:
text/plain
text/html
application/json
6. Send JSON Response
const data = { name: "Naveen", age: 20 };

res.writeHead(200, { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' });
res.end(JSON.stringify(data));
7. Request Information
console.log(req.url);      // URL
console.log(req.method);   // GET, POST, etc.
8. Why Use Express Instead?

Problems with http module:

Code becomes lengthy
Routing becomes complex
Hard to manage in large projects

That is why Express.js is preferred.

9. Express Server Example (Quick)
const express = require('express');
const app = express();

app.get('/', (req, res) => {
    res.send("Home Page");
});

app.listen(3000, () => {
    console.log("Server running on port 3000");
});
10. Interview Definition

Creating a server in Node.js involves using the http module to handle client requests and send responses over a specified port.

Final Summary
Use http.createServer() to create server
Use req and res to handle request and response
Use server.listen(port) to start server
Routing can be handled manually or using Express
Express is preferred for scalable applications
